    "caption": "North America's calmest cliff-dweller.",
    "shortDescription": "Mountain goats are not actually true goats — they're more closely related to antelopes — but they live on cliffs so steep that no predator bothers to follow them. Their hoof pads are almost rubbery, gripping rock the way a climbing shoe grips a wall, and a notch in each hoof acts like a brake to stop them sliding backwards. Fun fact: Mountain goats can stand on a ledge the width of a credit card without flinching."
